3.1.3 Marginal distributions of two-way tables¶

marginal distribution = the distribution of each variable seperately

  • The marginal distributions can be found from the table by summing down the rows or columns

Use apply() function to apply the sum() function to the rows or the columns.

apply(x, 1, sum) <- sum the rows

apply(x, 2, sum) <- sum the columns

Use margin.table() function as well.

margin.table(x, 1) <- row sum

margin.table(x, 2) <- column sum

3.3.2 The correlation between two variables¶

The correlation between two variables numerically describes whether larger/smaller than average values of one variable are related to larger/smaller than average values of the other variable.

In [32]:
# Uncorrelated data sets
x <- rnorm(50, mean=1, sd=3)
y <- rnorm(50, mean=1, sd=1.5)
plot(x,y)
lines(c(1,1), c(-4,5), lty=2)
lines(c(-6,8),c(1,1),lty=2)
In [38]:
x <- rnorm(50, mean=1, sd=3)
y <- 0.5*x+rnorm(50, mean=0, sd=1)
plot(x,y)
lines(c(1,1), c(-5,5), lty=2)
lines(c(-6,8),c(1,1),lty=2)

The upper plot is weakly correlated, or nearly uncorrelated.

For the correlated data, the products $(x_i-\bar{x})(y_i-\bar{y})$ will tend to be positive, as this happens in both the upper-right and lower-left quadrants.

(In the upper-right quadrant, $(x_i-\bar{x})$ will have a positive value, and so does $(y_i-\bar{y})$. The product of the two positive values equals a positive value. In the lower-left quadrant, $(x_i-\bar{x})$ will have a negative value, and so does $(y_i-\bar{y})$. The product of the two negative values equals a negative value)

This is not the case for the uncorrelated data.

The quantity $\sum_{i}(x_i-\bar{x})(y_i-\bar{y})$ will be useful in describing the correlation between two variables.

To produce a numeric summary that can be used to compare data sets, this sum is scaled by a term related to the product of the sample standard deviations. With this scaling, the correlation only involves the respective z-scores, and the quantity is always between -1 and 1.

                    The Pearson correlation coefficient
$$r = cor(x,y) = \frac{\sum(x_i-\bar{x})(y_i-\bar{y})}{\sqrt{\sum(x_i-\bar{x})^2\sum(y_i-\bar{y})^2}} = \frac{1}{n-1}\sum(\frac{x_i-\bar{x}}{s_x})(\frac{y_i-\bar{y}}{s_y})$$

$s_x$ = standard deviation of a data vector x

$s_y$ = standard deviation of a data vector y

In [39]:
attach(homedata);attach(maydow);attach(kid.weights)

# cor() shows the correlation between two variables(method = Pearson's r)
cor(y1970, y2000)
cor(max.temp[-1], diff(DJA))

# doubtful about a linear relationship
cor(height, weight)
0.896215487264815
0.0102884615164777
0.823756369960437

The Spearman rank correlation

If the relationship between the variables is not linear but is increasing, we can still use the correlation coefficient.

The Spearman rank correlation is the Pearson correlation coefficient computed with the ranked data.

3.4 Simple linear regression¶

regression

https://ko.wikipedia.org/wiki/%ED%9A%8C%EA%B7%80%EB%B6%84%EC%84%9D

We say that variables $x$ and $y$ have a linear relationship in a mathematical sense we mean that $y = mx+b$, where $m$ is the slope of the line and $b$ the intercept. We call $x$ the independent variable and $y$ the dependent one.

In statistics, we don't assume these variables have an exact linear relationship: rather, the possibility for noise or error is taken into account.

Simple Linear Regression Model

$y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1x_i + \epsilon_i$

$\epsilon_i$ = error term (unknown)

$\beta_0, \beta_1$ = regression coefficients (unknown)

$x$ = predictor variable

$y$ = response variable

The term linear is about the way the regression coefficients are used.

$y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1x_i^2 + \epsilon_i$ is a linear model

$y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1\beta_2x_i + \epsilon_i$ is a non-linear(quadratic) model

The term simple is used to emphasize that only one predictor variable is used. In multiple regression models, more than one predictor variables are used.

Through a model, we estimate the coefficients that yield estimated response variables closest to the actual response variables. "Hats" denote the estimates.

$$\hat{y} = \hat{\beta_0} + \hat{\beta_1}x$$
In [137]:
x <- c(1,2,3,3,4,5)
y <- c(2.8, -2.3, -0.5, 1.5,2.9, 4.3)
plot(x,y, main=bquote(e[i]*" = "* hat(y[i])*"-"*hat(y[i])*" = actual - predicted"))
lines(0.5:5.5, 0.5:5.5-1.5)
text(1.5,2,expression(hat(y) == paste(hat(beta[0]) + hat(beta[1]))*"x"), cex=0.7)
text(3.5, -0.5, expression((paste(x[3],",",y[3]))), cex=0.7)
text(3.5, 1.4, expression((paste(x[3],",",hat(y[3])))), cex=0.7)
text(3, 0.6, expression(e[3] == paste(y[3]-hat(y[3]))), cex=0.7)
arrows(3,0.8,3,1.35, length=0.1)
arrows(3, 0.2, 3, -0.35, length=0.1)
arrows(1.8, 1.5, 2.2, 0.7, length=0.1)

Geometrically, the residual is the signed vertical distance of the point ($x_i, y_i$) to the prediction line as seen in the figure above. If the estimated line is a good one, these distances should be small.

The method of least squares chooses the line so that the sum of the squared residuals is as small as possible.

$$\hat{\beta_1} = \frac{\sum(x_i-\bar{x})(y_i-\bar{y})}{\sum(x_i-\bar{x})^2}$$$$\hat{\beta_0} = \bar{y} - \hat{\beta_1}\bar{x}$$

Interpreting, the regression line goes through the point ($\bar{x}, \bar{y}$) and has slope given by $\hat{\beta_1}$

3.4.5 Outliers in the regression model¶

Two types of outliers

  • in the univariate sense = a data point that doesn't fit the pattern set by the bulk of the data
  • in the regression model = points that are far from the trend or pattern of the data
In [197]:
f <- CO2~perCapita
In [219]:
options(repr.plot.width = 6, repr.plot.height=6)
plot(f, data=emissions)
abline(lm(CO2~perCapita, data=emissions))
abline(lm(f, data=emissions, subset=-1), lty=2)
legend(7000, 6000, c("With U.S.", "Without U.S."), bty='n', lty=c(1,2))
text(26000, 6500, "United States")

'United States' is an outlier for the CO2 variable, but not for the per-capita GDP
-> an outlier in the bivariate sense, as it stands far off from the trend set by the rest of the data

3.4.6 Resistant regression lines: lqs() and rlm()¶

regression coefficients are subject to strong influences from outliers.

  • Alternatives to the mean and standard deviation -> median or the IQR

There are several resistant alternatives for the regression line.

1) Least-trimmed squares
The least-squares regression line is found conceptually by calculating for each line the sum of the squared residuals and then minimizing this value over all possible lines.
Least trimmed squares does the same, only the sum of the squared residuals is replaced by the sum of the $q$ smallest squared residuals, where $q$ is roughly $\frac{n}{2}$.
The least-trimmed squares algorithm is implemented in the lqs() function from the MASS package.

In [222]:
# library(MASS)
plot(f, data=emissions)
abline(lm(f, data=emissions, subset=-1), lty=2)
abline(lqs(f, data=emissions), lty=3, col="red")

2) Resistant regression using rlm()

It is not as resistant to outliers as lqs() by default, but can be made so with the method = "MM".

In [223]:
# library(MASS)
plot(f, data=emissions)
abline(lm(f, data=emissions, subset=-1), lty=2)
abline(lqs(f, data=emissions), lty=3, col="red")
abline(rlm(f, data=emissions, method="MM"), lty=4, col="blue")
In [225]:
plot(f, data=emissions)
abline(lm(CO2~perCapita, data=emissions))
abline(lm(f, data=emissions, subset=-1), lty=2, col=2)
abline(lqs(f, data=emissions), lty=3, col=3)
abline(rlm(f, data=emissions, method="MM"), lty=4, col=4)
the.labels <- c("lm", "lm w/o 1", "least trimmed squares", "rlm with MM")
the.ltys <- 1:4
the.cols <- 1:4
legend(5000, 6000, legend=the.labels, lty=the.ltys, col=the.cols, bty="n")

3.4.7 Trend lines¶

If a scatterplot suggests some relationship, but not an obvious transformation to make a linear relationship, we can still superimpose a "trend line" on top of the data using one of the many scatterplot smoothing techniques available in R.

  • scatter.smooth(): uses the loess() function
  • smooth.spline(): cubinc splines
  • supsmu(): Friedman's "super smoother" algorithm
In [232]:
# Example 3.9

# lty = line type, lwd = line width
lines(smooth.spline(temps ~ days), lty=2, lwd=2)
lines(supsmu(days, temps), lty=3, lwd=2)
